  <static seed="1443" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations4.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{-2t+5}{t+5}} = {-\frac{2t}{t+10}} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{10\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{\left(t+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(t+10\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{-2t+5}{t+5}} \amp = {-\frac{2t}{t+10}} \\
   {\frac{-2t+5}{t+5}} \cdot {\left(t+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(t+10\right)} \amp = {-\frac{2t}{t+10}} \cdot {\left(t+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(t+10\right)} \\
   {\left(-2t+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(t+10\right)} \amp = {-2t\mathopen{}\left(t+5\right)} \\
   {-2t^{2}-20t+5t+50} \amp = {-2t^{2}-10t} \\
   -5t \amp = -50 \\
   t \amp = 10
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>{\left(t+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(t+10\right)} \ne 0</m>, which is equivalent to <m>t \ne -5</m> and <m>t \ne -10</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>t = 10</m>.</p>
</solution>
